author: @BakedBeansSpam
textdisplay:
The formatting, transmission, receipt and translation of information for most effective human absorption/interaction for any given purpose of the publishers and recipients, using all senses (omni-modal?) appears to be a set of processes that will be automated and optimized by AI, rendering all skills related thereto obsolete except for recreational purposes or as part of the learning process itself. Think horse riding, think coding (very soon).

So what is left? Learning ability, understanding and interrogation as foundational skills in every modality. Then... Epistemology, imagination, curiosity, theoretical academic pursuits, new definitions of intelligence, inspiration, creativity, empathy, extrasensory exploration, spirituality, ethics, compassion, love, service?....Others? Which of these can/will be ultimately be surpassed and when?

It seems inevitable that we are entering a new age characterized by unimaginable acceleration of human progress in every conceivable and unlimited as yet inconceivable fields of endeavor.

The evaluation of individual ability - perhaps this will be rendered obsolete. People will either do or will not do. Can or cannot. There may be no subjective evaluation of anything.

How many agricultural job types remain in high income nations at scale? How many are essentially supervisory jobs overseeing machines that have substituted most menial tasks. Our world now sustains an 8 billion population estimated to peak at 10 billion before declining again. In the last 100 years it has grown 4X. Meanwhile the agricultural workforce has in high income countries has declined 10X. U.S. is 1.36% of workforce despite being self-sufficient and a major food exporter.

Why would we imagine that all knowledge work as we currently understand it will decline at anything other than an exponentially greater rate. There was a massive inflection point in agriculture in wealthy countries post-WW2 in the 1950s as focus turned to automation of farming.

The computer revolution started for the same reasons at the same time. Neither have reduced unemployment in high income nations. That's where materially all the academic research takes place, especially when one considers the import of STEM talent from India, China, UK, EU etc especially at the post-doctoral level.

author: @akagordon
textdisplay:
There's a few paid services out there for summarizing scientific articles, and trained specifically to that end. They work really well in my experience, but I've only used one to do about six articles and a thesis. The thesis I entered piecemeal, like in this video, and it worked the best for summary. This type of tech will be great for deciding what articles deserve closer attention, or getting a firm grasp of new concepts.

I've been asking ChatGPT chemistry questions, mostly about spectroscopy and microscopy, then critiquing the answers. It seems to answer those at about a sophomore level with almost perfect accuracy. When I ask it to elaborate on key points, it delivers them with confidence, though almost every time one or more points are inaccurate, or it omits something important. It's still an astounding model. Seeing where this tech can go is exciting, especially within the context of scientific communication and education!

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: THanks for sharing your experiences. As I experiment further with ChatGPT primarily by giving the prompt more context and instructions on do and don‚Äôts I found it to give more favorable results.

author: @corey4448
textdisplay: Can you share paid services you're talking about?

author: @akagordon
textdisplay:
@@corey4448 it's been about 18 months since I used it, but I think the one I had the best experience with was Scholarcy. I've also tried QuillBot and it was pretty good. While not dedicated to science, I know some AI specialists that swear by Jasper.

I bet by this time next year, or sooner, ChatGPT will be the best out of them, especially if you also need to write text or code. They've already added a feature where you can give the title and authors of a paper and it will summarize it for you! No need to copy the text into the prompt for most published papers up to 2021.

author: @erics9214
textdisplay:
People appear to be too easily taken in by ChatGPT. Much of what it does isn't in the least miraculous. In this particular example, you can Google this code and find pretty much the exact same code, including the comments. It looks like ChatGPT did that and then did a little editing on the comments.
If you ask ChatGPT for an essay, the essay is very formulaic. If you read a few of them, they all begin to sound the same. I messed around with doing some queries and eventually got ChatGPT to write a sonnet comparing Donald Trump to a chicken. But there was nothing particularly original about the sonnet. It was kind of a clever word salad in sonnet format. No doubt something of a striking accomplishment in its generality, but to call this Artificial Intelligence, as the general public understands that term, is a bit of a stretch. What it does is clever, in a sense, but it is not in any way "intelligent". It just has a giant database (the internet) and is clever about mish-mashing that data together in a way that easily fools people into thinking that it actually "knows" something.

author: @dylanloader3869
textdisplay:
As much as I think it's great you're getting sponsorships.

Mito is a company with a purposefully opaque pay structure. They claim to be free in hopes of getting people onboard with personal licensing, then leveraging the familiarity to push business licensing.
It's a fine approach if it's done transparently (eg. Anaconda), but their lack of transparency is one of the reasons they've been critiqued on Reddit.

I would advise anyone thinking of using this product to ask "How many SAAS companies with a single product line try to hide their fee structure this much?"

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: Thanks for your comment, as for this and prior Mito videos there has been no sponsorship from the Mito team, if there was I would activate the option for the video that the video is being sponsored (a recent Sponsorships we had was from Coursera). We have partnered with the Mito team for educational purpose of sharing how to use the tool. And yes, we have yet to see the pay structure of the tool as the situation unfolds.

author: @gama3181
textdisplay:
I'm biologist. I found a lot of blogs were says that the protein folding problem is solved. I don't think so. Indeed, most of the authors of these blogs are data scientist/analyst, programers, etc and i noted that the protein biology background is only enougth to comunicate the idea but not enougth to take to the problem seriously. There is a lot of hues with proteins like chaperons, moon-ligth, intrinsically disordered, prions, etc.

AF2 it's awesome and would like to read the paper rigth now! We have to stay alert for that. Maybe in the next 2-6 years with the advances of transformers, graph CNN and the low cost of GPUs the protein folding will be solverd

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: Certainly agree with your point. Very excited of the direction that AI is taking the field and there is indeed definitely a lot more details that needs to be addressed as you had suggested.

author: @gama3181
textdisplay:
@@DataProfessor And all together will learn this with data professor :)

I hope that AF2 bring more interest in solving the protein sequence-function problem. It's very interesting how Craig Venter have to put inside his microbial synthetic genome proteins with unknow functions that are needed to be alive. And with metagenomics we always found unannotated sequences.

There are very interesting papers like this
"Neural networks to learn protein sequence-function relationships from deep mutational scanning data"

Or GitHub repos specialized in this kind of literature:
https://github.com/yangkky/Machine-learning-for-proteins

author: @SUGATORAY
textdisplay:
For images and videos GitHub now allows direct copy and pasting into the markdown, without having to separately uploading the file(s) first to the repo. When you paste the image into the markdown on GitHub, the file gets stored somewhere and generates a ready to use link to the image.

This is useful, however, if you want to maintain a repo with all its assets easily accessible, I think uploading the media files to a known place is more reliable and reproducible.

textdisplay:
Nice explanation! Thank you! I have two questions, though.
(i) The webpage is visually appealing, but is there a quick way to redirect to the original repository in case somebody wants to run the code?
(ii) Can I insert the result of interactive data visualization into the webpage? For example, the result from Plotly can be saved as a HTML file. I was told that Markdown cannot do this. So only by editing the HTML code of the webpage, perhaps?

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay:
Hi, thanks for watching!
(1) This can be done with a simple link in Markdown using [Link text](http://url/)
(2) Yes, there is support for HTML on GitHub Pages, perhaps a topic for a future video? A workaround is to use a simple link to the HTML containing the interactive data visualization

author: @arielleung3917
textdisplay: @@DataProfessor Merci beaucoup! I'm thinking about making the interactive visualization immediately available on the webpage. Love to see a video about this! ^_^

author: @ansonnn_
textdisplay:
If you google search "How to insert Python Graph into HTML file" then im sure you can find the guide that you want.
But to be able to use a HTML file for GitHub pages, you need to create a new HTML file inside the repo and name it exactly as "index.html" without the quotes.
Also, you can only use HTML markup language instead of Markdown language for the index.html. One workaround is to copy the HTML markup from the Chrome DevTools after you have created the page with the README file, this is a bit inconvenient unless you know how to write HTML markups, for which you can just directly write your entire markup inside of the index.html file.

author: @_danfiz
textdisplay: Hi. I am very new to programming. Are C and C++ language obsolete and not relevant to learn these days? Because everywhere I read, most would mention about R and Python.

author: @akeylawhite9217
textdisplay: Not obsolete at all, they're just used for different projects and objectives than R or Python.  Linux is largely written in C.  The Python interpreter itself is written in C.  Programs and more complicated programs might be written in C++ (or C#, or other various flavors of C).  Python is generally used for Data Science, Web Server back ends, or prototyping programs, though it can do most anything, it's not the quickest..  R is pretty much for statistics / data science.  C languages are more difficult to learn and write code in, but their execution speed generally is significantly faster than interpreted languages like Python.  It's really just about what the goal is you want to accomplish.

author: @priyanaik1088
textdisplay: hello sir, can u plz tell which dataset is used to find binding energy when ligand interact with protein?

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: To computationally obtain the binding energy of protein-ligand complex we can use molecular docking. For more accurate results we can use free energy calculation. For definitive answer we‚Äôll have to use experimental methods such as calculating the Kd (binding constant). In the biological context, we can experimentally measure the biological response induced by the ligand binding the protein via Ki, IC50, EC50, etc. My favorite data source for small molecule data is ChEMBL and there‚Äôs PubChem and BindingDB.

author: @priyanaik1088
textdisplay: @@DataProfessor Thank u sir for ur quick response. I have one more doubt. I have one more doubt sir. In Chembl database which column indicate the binding energy

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: @@priyanaik1088 Hi, ChEMBL does not provide binding energy, for that you will need to use a molecular docking software which can produce something similar called the docking energy. What ChEMBL does provide are the Ki, IC50, EC50 values and their values are normally indicated by the column called ‚ÄúStandard_Value‚Äù

author: @lorenzologiudice2023
textdisplay:
Hi, I've watched a lot of your videos and found them really interesting and well curated (I love your infographics and I find them really useful).

I wanted to kindly ask you for clarification: I understood that "Data Preparation", "Data Preprocessing", "Scrub Data" are all synonyms, but I don't understand if "obtaining data" is part of the "data preprocessing":
in the video "How to Become a Data Scientist (Learning Path and Skill Sets Needed)" I saw that "Data Preprogessing" includes "Obtaining Data", "Handling Missing Data" (I also saw the related video), "Data Cleaning", "Feature Engineering" and "Feature Selection" but in these two videos both in the "lifecycle", both in the "CRISP-DM framework" and in the "OSEMN framework" the phase of obtaining the data is excluded if I understand correctly.

I saw that you had in mind to make a series of videos on "data preprocessing" (of which the video "Data Pre-processing in R: Handling Missing Data" is part I think): do you think to carry it on? that would be really cool

One more thing I would like to have clear in mind: is "data wrangling" a part of "data preprocessing"?

Keep it up!
Greetings from Italy, Lorenzo

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay:
Hi Lorenzo, thanks for the question and glad the contents and infographics are helpful. I've also written several blog posts on the Medium platform which may go into a little more depth for the topics covered in the videos, some of which are on the same topics as in the YouTube video. http://bit.ly/chanin-medium
Yes, the terms from several of these data science frameworks have been introduced at different point in time by different organization and people. And yes the terms share synonymous meanings such as what you have mentioned Data Preparation, Data Pre-processing, Scrub Data and also Data Wrangling. As the initial data may be containing missing data, contain redundancy or typos then we will need to clean the data.

The How to become a data scientist video highlights the common skillsets that is essential for a data scientist and does not really cover the data science life cycle. I'll soon be releasing a video on How to Build a Machine Learning Model soon based on this article https://towardsdatascience.com/how-to-build-a-machine-learning-model-439ab8fb3fb1

The Data Science Process article is at https://towardsdatascience.com/the-data-science-process-a19eb7ebc41b

Hope this helps. Thanks for the support of the channel.

author: @lorenzologiudice2023
textdisplay:
@@DataProfessor wow, thanks for the stormy response!

I had already read "The Data Science Process" but I hadn't read "How to Build a Machine Learning Model" yet!

You were very kind and above all very clear! Thanks a lot!

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: Life science has other OMICS data for which data science can be applied to in making sense of these data. Aside from genomics, there's proteomics (proteins), metabolomics (metabolites), transcriptomics (RNA), interactomics (macromolecular interactions), etc. The use cases are quite diverse but mostly for therapeutic, diagnostics and for furthering understanding into the basic sciences.

Hello! great video. I have to point out something you said about the function np.random.normal(): You are NOT generating a distribution in range from 0 to 100, as you mentioned in min. 0:38; instead you are generating 100 points with a mean of 0 and a std of 10. Therefore:
x = np.random.normal(mean,std,num. of points) .
That's why you get negative values for the x array as well.

author: @slhermit
textdisplay:
Good and motivational advice. DS is an ocean. The main issue I had when trying to learn DS is that not knowing my next step. I tend to learn everything and felt lost (I still have this feeling to some extent, not sure where to move in terms of the industry)

I think data scientist are of two main types: Generalist and Domain-specific data scientist. Most generalists appear to work in finance/sales or internet/tech companies. These guys are likely to have more statistics/econometric/engineering background. Of course, you can find specialist among these generalists as well (or become a specialist over years of experience or with advanced degree).

Then the domain-specific data scientists are PhD-scientist who typically work in biotech/chemistry industry.

Most data scientists are in finance/sales/internet companies and getting a position in these companies is relatively easier than getting a position in biotech/chemistry companies that typically demand expertise conducting scientific research (this are actually scientist jobs, scientists who know domain-specific ML models and cloud computing)

author: @francisdelacruz6439
textdisplay: Looked at several analyst roles in business such as those related to sales in Insurance companies and retail, they dont seem to require python at all or that much.  Whats used is Excel, Tableau / Power BI and if more advanced SQL. Why the focus on Python and R when these roles are likely to be those used extensively not by analysts but senior level Data Scientists? Is this the standard in Tech or Big Tech FAANG roles? It appears for a lot of companies these higher skill roles are not used in their daily usage of data for analyst positions in their actual work. Maybe its an HR thing requiring higher skill levels on paper like requiring an MS for junior data analyst roles, tsk...

author: @KenJee_ds
textdisplay: Really good observation here. For data analyst roles, bi tools & sql are the most important things. Programming is a plus and can help you get ahead. This content is a bit more for people looking to go right into data science. Some overlap, but definitely different priority for coding

textdisplay: @@KenJee_ds Thanks, yes kind of a warfare to look better on CV. Not to fault them if there are many applicants for a position they may get the most skilled with or higher qualification even for less senior roles. Nice videos, just getting to watch the channel. Cheers.

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: Hi Hans, sorry if it was unclear, had to keep it under 1 minute. Let me try to explain the video a bit further. The top panel is the command line where you can run your Streamlit app from (streamlit run app.py). The middle panel is your code editor or IDE where you type in the code for your Streamlit app. The bottom panel is the web browser that allows you to see the Streamlit app (which will be displayed when the app is rendered via streamlit run app.py as mentioned above).

author: @StijnHommes
textdisplay: That is a website. Not an app. You don't even know the difference.

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: I beg to differ. Streamlit allows building web apps that users can interact with, e.g. upload data, run calculations, build machine learning models, customize parameters via slider widgets, etc. I‚Äôd like to think of websites as primarily use to provide static content (images/text). More details in this article https://www.freecodecamp.org/news/difference-between-a-website-and-a-web-application/

author: @StijnHommes
textdisplay:
@@DataProfessor By that definition, websites don't exist. We interact with everything online.
An app, is a standalone program for a mobile device. A website is something with an URL. There is nothing to be gained by blending the two together and not making a clear distinction.

author: @dylansund3479
textdisplay: @@StijnHommes nothing to be gained by allowing data interaction without a download which needs to be redownloaded when updates get pushed. Application doesn‚Äôt have to be mobile either. Ever used word or excel?

author: @sebastianrivas887
textdisplay:
Hello! great video. I have to point out something you said about the function np.random.normal(): You are NOT generating a distribution in range from 0 to 100, as you mentioned in min. 0:38; instead you are generating 100 points with a mean of 0 and a std of 10. Therefore:
x = np.random.normal(mean,std,num. of points) .
That's why you get negative values for the x array as well.

Hello Professor
How do we define plagiarism in Data Science ?

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay:
Ken Jee made a video on this very topic of plagiarism https://youtu.be/vQGJvmhpq_s
Plagiarism is typically defined as claiming the work of others as oneself usually without any acknowledgement of the original source for the content. Proper credit and acknowledgement of the content should be made if one intends to use the content.

author: @johirislam8174
textdisplay: i have some other quaries regarding Differential gene expression  analysis in R .I want to compare two datasets differentially expressed gene that i have taken from GEO database ,how can i do that.For example one data set contain 108 DEG and the other contain 70 so i want to see the common gene between this two dataset. author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay: A simple union analysis can be done to discern the comment sets of genes. A no-code option is to use the Venny tool where you just input the list of gene names into separate text box and you can get the common set of genes. https://bioinfogp.cnb.csic.es/tools/venny/

textdisplay: Hi DataProfessor, Do you think this sort of approach will assisting in getting the the breakthrough in finally understanding how some anaesthetics work on the brain?

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay:
Insights can be gain on what molecular features give rise to the observed actions of drugs. Particularly, interpretations can be made by analyzing the feature importance from e.g. Random forest's Gini index or from Shap values which helps to see the contribution of molecular features. Holistically, we can think of this as:
1. Drug ‚Üí 2. Target Protein ‚Üí 3. Various Biomolecular Interaction (Biochemical pathways) ‚Üí 4. Phenotype (Observable end outcome )
Thus, a single machine learning model can help to figure out steps 1 and 2. Whereas the events that happens in steps 3 and 4 is quite complex and requires further analysis.

author: @subhanbasha8813
textdisplay:
Hello Professor,
Is it recommend to code all the machine learning algorithms from scratch so that I can learn math behind it or just understand and start to code?

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay:
Hi, I would recommend to understand ML algorithms at a high-level, then start to implement a data science project. Once you have done this and understand all components of the data science lifecycle. The key is to know just enough to tackle the problem at hand then slowly evolve by reading more details into various topics on how you can improve the model.Tina Huang has a great video on learning data science in her recent video https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Axu4tJl8gbM
Also check out my Medium article Learn Data Science in 10 Steps https://towardsdatascience.com/10-things-i-wish-i-knew-about-learning-data-science-7a30bfb91759

author: @KenJee_ds
textdisplay: I generally recommend starting with one programming language and learning it very well. If you know one well, I find that it is easier to pick up other ones in the future. I personally like Python, but R is also a good one for the field.

author: @emanuelrodriguezbedeman5344
textdisplay:
@@abdallahsiyabi4784 Sorry for not answering fast Sir, I didn't get the notification.


For Stats I recommend you to start from Descriptive statistics and them move on to inferential statistics. If you don't understand very well this concepts I recommend you to learn some Linear Algebra. You can find this concepts very well explained in youtube.

But again, as Ken Jee said, Kaggle is one great place to learn Data Science, you should start learning Python in there.

Hi ken,

author: @KenJee_ds
textdisplay: I would start small with a very specific project in mind. I would focus on answering questions or solving problems over learning individual skills. There will always be too many skills to learn, but these skills are only valuable if they help you to solve problems. Inverting the playing field can make things more manageable. I hope this helps!

author: @CleverNameTBD
textdisplay: For accountability, I agree with you and glad it works for you. On the flip side, telling people is one major reason why some people never stick to their resolutions. It's a hidden piece of advice to never tell your wishes or they won't come true. Many people get a dopamine rush from the "oh wow. So cool of you for wanting to do that stuff!" And that's enough reward for them instead of actually achieving it. Again, I agree with you. But people who fall into the dopamine event need to be aware of their behavior in case this strategy doesn't work for them. That said, I am learning python, sql and would love machine learning lol.

Biologist here! I am a completely beginner in programming. So what I did was to look for free classes. I started watching and following the cs50 introduction to programming. The videos are so good! David Mathel, the professor, is an extremely teacher.

author: @matattz
textdisplay:
Honestly what helped me the most was the mindset that learning the basics like pandas, numpy, seaborn etc are just TOOLS you have to master for the actual Data Science things you want to do. Don‚Äôt dive to deep into those things, you can and will become better over time but you have to actually start practicing with it!! Start a project and apply the things you learned. Then step by step try and understand the theory behind Machine Learning, start with the book Data Science for Business by Foster Provost. It‚Äôs an amazing entry for beginners to grasp the overall concept and how you need Data Science in the business world. Next you should read, practical statistics for Data Scientists. Also beginner friendly but very good to read. After that read Hands on Machine Learning with Scikit learn. Amazing book and more advanced then t he other ones, that‚Äôs when you start to get more into the math behind ML. Parallel to that book you can start watching the machine learning playlist from Bloomberg here on YouTube to understand how the Algorithms work exactly and what you need to do for optimization. This is we‚Äôre you also want to get practical, and I would recommend the book xGBoost from Matt Harrison. Great great book ! To get an expert at Pandas you should definitely also check out his Book effective pandas. A life saver.
And the most important thing, you already found one of the best tutors for practical Machine Learning in Krish, keep watching his videos and you are good.
Next you can learn Deep Learning by Andrew Ng on Coursera or watch many videos for free here on YouTube. He‚Äôs an absolute legend and you should definitely check him out.

If you do all of this, trust me you will become a weapon and you are on an amazing path!

author: @amdenis
textdisplay:
Love what you do and did to get there. One thing, while three years of 50 hours a week is a great base, and probably better with some who got a bachelors degree in computer science from decent college, a solid masters degree from a great school takes about 10,000 hours of study, a few years of internships and work, and all the great stuff you did. Also, schools vary widely, and I can tell you that I can often tell that someone went to a top university for their computer science degree. For example, it is not surprising that the type of student and programmer from let‚Äôs say MIT where the typical SAT is mid-1500‚Äôs is different than the average from a local community college. Of course there are amazing students and professionals from many schools, and some of the most successful never went to college. However, averages mean something too.

The most important thing you have done is to solidly start down a great path. I am sure you will stay with it.
Be the best you!

textdisplay: Hi all, i'm getting ready to learn machine learning. I'm currently finishing up my math review (calculus, linear/matrix algebra) , i don't think i need to review statistics and probability because i'm an epidemiologist and have been doing lots of statistical modeling (linear regression, logistic regression, survival analysis, longitudinal data analysis, structural equation modeling with latent variables , etc... Should i go straight to take a machine learning class on Udemy  ( they said people who are new to Python like me are welcome as well  ) after my math review which i will  be completing in 2 weeks (i already took Mathematics for machine learning specialisation on Coursera by Imperial college London, i also took linear algebra for engineers on Coursera by Dr Jef Chasnov, Hong Kong university, i also took another calculus course on coursera by  Dr Jim Fowler). author: @pratikpandey2568
textdisplay:
Roadmap: How to Learn Machine Learning in 6 Months
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MOdlp1d0PNA&list=WL&index=13&ab_channel=IDEAS

Just Build Something with data

Learn: Maths, Algebra, Statistic, Probability, Calculus

Where to learn:
MIT Linear Algebra Open course
MIT Calculus Open course
MIT Stats and Prob Algebra Open course

Python Vs R: Both are good just choose one and start
Do interview questions, Learn, Master them, Build a project.

Find Data: Webscrape, API
Clean Data: you spend 99 percent of your time here

Choose your algorithm
Visualize results

Schedule

Learn the Math ( 2-3 months)
Learn the Programming ( 1 month)
Machine Learning tutorial and test Projects. ( 1 - 2 Months )
Short-term Passion Projects. ( 1+ month)

It takes a lot of time and discipline

You are going to Fail a lot. Its software who cares
Your models may not be predictive. That's the result. Null is as good as nonnull if you did it right.
Track your projects on Github and Write up your results.

author: @KenJee_ds
textdisplay:
Thanks for watching Humberto! So I recommend the kaggle.com micro courses to start learning python for data science. They are free and take you through the exact tools you would need for data science. Basically python -> basic ml algorithms -> more advanced ml algorithms -> sql -> deep learning. If you want something more structured, I recommend the 365 data science materials for learning python as well (this one is paid). If that is something you're interested in, these are some discount codes for the coursework: 47% Discount on 1 year: https://365datascience.pxf.io/Z7gXQ or
20% off one month: https://365datascience.pxf.io/NjbEv. I hope this helps!

author: @mael2839
textdisplay:
After having ‚Äútalked‚Äù with some low level AI, I was astonished. There was a very small amount of times where I could see through its mirage. One AI had me legitimately second guessing if it was human or not. I resorted to reverse psychology to finding out if it was human or not. It really played on my second guessing myself.

This led me to think about Rasputin Warmind AI (Destiny 2).

When you said about thinking on what you want it to do. The first thing that came to my mind was ‚Äúfree will‚Äù.

I then thought I would like to make an AI which would pass for being a friend, engaged in physical debates, have conversations of pointless matters. Retaining what I have previously said and using that information to talk to me, argue certain things in debates by finding flaws in my previous statements.

Ultimately I want to create a Warmind AI which is built on empathy and compassion. This would make it alive, it would be cruel to make a Warmind AI feel empathy, but I don‚Äôt want it to kill without understanding the morality of the actions.

It would weigh up the greater good, but it would never forget about its moral obligations.

My ultimate goal is to have it defy my direct commands while explaining to me why it does not obey. I want it to develop on its own to make its own choices. I do not want to be Clovis Bray.

textdisplay:
I started watching ur videos for the first time now. After kene,Krish and U combo.on single platform .
I am a asst.prof in electrical engineering back ground. Wanted to understand data science .
Tell me , is data science , AI, machine learning,deep learning everything interlinked ? Can we isolate them by profession. ? Or one should have every thing known ?

author: @DataProfessor
textdisplay:
Thanks for your question Janardhan.
This is a great question. Coming to the field for the first time may be a bit confusing at first.
I've recently written a Medium article "10 Things I Wish I Knew About Learning Data Science" that contains practical advice from my 15 years in data science.
Please check it out: https://towardsdatascience.com/10-things-i-wish-i-knew-about-learning-data-science-7a30bfb91759

The keywords that you have asked about, if I could reorder them in hierarchical manner it would look like this:
artificial intelligence, data science, machine learning, deep learning

So everything is broadly belonging to artificial intelligence. Data science deals with making sense of data through the use of CRISP-DM or OSEMN principles essentially comprising of domain understanding, data collection/pre-processing, model building, model interpretation and iteration back to whichever steps that needs improvement. Machine learning refers to the learning algorithms that you can use for "model building". Deep learning is a type of neural network that has for the past 5 years gained significant traction in the ML and DS community. For Data science, aside from machine learning you will also be using Statistics for exploratory data analysis in order to gain a brief understand of the data along with various disciplines (please have a look at my infographic on the skillsets of a data scientist along with the YouTube video I made):
- Links to infographic and video is provided in my recent Medium article "10 Things I Wish I Knew About Learning Data Science"
https://towardsdatascience.com/10-things-i-wish-i-knew-about-learning-data-science-7a30bfb91759
- Here's the direct link to the infographic
https://github.com/dataprofessor/infographic/blob/master/04-Data-Science-Landscape.JPG
- YouTube video on "How to Become a Data Scientist (Learning Path and Skill Sets Needed)"
https://youtu.be/jhImgx8I8oI

There are several articles on Medium for further reference:
- https://towardsdatascience.com/ai-machine-learning-deep-learning-explained-simply-7b553da5b960
- https://medium.com/fbdevclagos/artificial-intelligence-machine-learning-deep-learning-and-data-science-whats-the-difference-e82f9e7094a
- https://medium.com/ai-in-plain-english/data-science-vs-artificial-intelligence-vs-machine-learning-vs-deep-learning-50d3718d51e5

Hope this helps and welcome to data science!

P.S. Please check out my Data Science 101 playlist on general concepts and practical videos:
http://bit.ly/dataprofessor-ds101

textdisplay: @@jithendrayenugula7137 I would say that both are rather different. A personal blog would be nice to have and the URL of which can be placed in your Medium profile. Thinking in terms of visibility, publishing in a publication on Medium will also a large pool of audience already subscribed to big publications such as Towards Data Science or Towards AI to see the articles that you write, from which they can possibly visit your Medium profile and see your blog website's URL. author: @justinlam5565
textdisplay:
As always, great video!


One idea I haven't heard of before is focusing on one project and learning only the specific skills necessary for that project. Everyone's experienced the overwhelm when it comes to beginning the Data Science / ML / DL journey, and we're usually hit with the, "learn all of statistics, all of programming, and all of math" mentality that is drilled into our heads. This can be enough to scare people away, and your advice really combats this while touching on the idea of running on passion and things you enjoy by picking a personal project or use case.




It's really cool to see that you have a specific domain that you stay in for projects (sports and sports betting). My question is:


Do you stay within that domain at work?


If you do, do you suggest that we each choose a specific domain as well, and cater towards that when building a career and finding a job?
If you don't, would you agree that it's still valuable to choose a specific domain? Do you think that your experience and expertise in sports / sports betting transfers over to your current job/position?


Thanks for the video Ken!
